(lp3
VHave you ever wanted to stay young a little longer
p4
aVand put off aging?
p5
aVThis is a dream of the ages.
p6
aVBut scientists have for a long time
p7
aVthought this just was never going to be possible.
p8
aVThey thought you just wear out, there's nothing you can do about it \u2014
p9
aVkind of like an old shoe.
p10
aVBut if you look in nature,
p11
aVyou see that different kinds of animals
p12
aVcan have really different lifespans.
p13
aVNow these animals are different from one another,
p14
aVbecause they have different genes.
p15
aVSo that suggests
p16
aVthat somewhere in these genes, somewhere in the DNA,
p17
aVare genes for aging,
p18
aVgenes that allow them to have different lifespans.
p19
aVSo if there are genes like that,
p20
aVthen you can imagine that,
p21
aVif you could change one of the genes in an experiment,
p22
aVan aging gene,
p23
aVmaybe you could slow down aging and extend lifespan.
p24
aVAnd if you could do that, then you could find the genes for aging.
p25
aVAnd if they exist and you can find them,
p26
aVthen maybe one could eventually do something about it.
p27
aa(lp28
VSo we've set out to look for genes that control aging.
p29
aVAnd we didn't study any of these animals.
p30
aVInstead, we studied a little, tiny, round worm called C. elegans,
p31
aVwhich is just about the size of a comma in a sentence.
p32
aVAnd we were really optimistic that we could find something
p33
aVbecause there had been a report of a long-lived mutant.
p34
aVSo we started to change genes at random,
p35
aVlooking for long-lived animals.
p36
aVAnd we were very lucky to find
p37
aVthat mutations that damage one single gene called daf-2
p38
aVdoubled the lifespan of the little worm.
p39
aa(lp40
VSo you can see in black, after a month \u2014
p41
aVthey're very short-lived; that's why we like to study them
p42
aVfor studies of aging \u2014
p43
aVin black, after a month, the normal worms are all dead.
p44
aVBut at that time,
p45
aVmost of the mutant worms are still alive.
p46
aVAnd it isn't until twice as long
p47
aVthat they're all dead.
p48
aVAnd now I want to show what they actually look like in this movie here.
p49
aVSo the first thing you're going to see
p50
aVis the normal worm
p51
aVwhen it's about college student age \u2014 a young adult.
p52
aVIt's quite a cute little fellow.
p53
aVAnd next you're going to see the long-lived mutant when it's young.
p54
aVSo this animal is going to live twice as long.
p55
aVIs it miserable? It doesn't seem to be.
p56
aVIt's active. You can't tell the difference really.
p57
aVAnd they can be completely fertile \u2014
p58
aVhave the same number of progeny as the normal worms do.
p59
aa(lp60
VNow get out your handkerchiefs here.
p61
aVYou're going to see, in just two weeks,
p62
aVthe normal worms are old.
p63
aVYou can see the little head moving down at the bottom there.
p64
aVBut everything else is just lying there.
p65
aVThe animal's clearly in the nursing home.
p66
aVAnd if you look at the tissues of the animal, they're starting to deteriorate.
p67
aVYou know, even if you've never seen one of these little C. elegans \u2014
p68
aVwhich probably most of you haven't seen one \u2014
p69
aVyou can tell they're old \u2014 isn't that interesting?
p70
aa(lp71
VSo there's something about aging that's kind of universal.
p72
aVAnd now here is the daf-2 mutant.
p73
aVOne gene is changed out of 20,000, and look at it.
p74
aVIt's the same age, but it's not in the nursing home;
p75
aVit's going skiing.
p76
aVThis is what's really cool: it's aging more slowly.
p77
aVIt takes this worm two days
p78
aVto age as much as the normal worm ages in one day.
p79
aVAnd when I tell people about this,
p80
aVthey tend to think of maybe an 80 or 90 year-old person
p81
aVwho looks really good for being 90 or 80.
p82
aVBut it's really more like this:
p83
aVlet's say you're a 30 year-old guy \u2014 or in your 30s \u2014
p84
aVand you're a bachelor and you're dating people.
p85
aVAnd you meet someone you really like, you get to know her.
p86
aVAnd you're in a restaurant, and you say, "Well how old are you?"
