aVSo what is the daf-2 gene?
p95
aVWell as you know, genes, which are part of the DNA,
p96
aVthey're instructions to make a protein that does something.
p97
aVAnd the daf-2 gene
p98
aVencodes a hormone receptor.
p99
aVSo what you see in the picture there
p100
aVis a cell with a hormone receptor in red
p101
aVpunching through the edge of the cell.
p102
aVSo part of it is like a baseball glove.
p103
aVPart of it's on the outside,
p104
aVand it's catching the hormone as it comes by in green.
p105
aVAnd the other part is on the inside
p106
aVwhere it sends signals into the cell.
p107
aa(lp108
VOkay, so what is the daf-2 receptor
p109
aVtelling the inside of the cell?
p110
aVI just told you that, if you make a mutation in the daf-2 gene cell,
p111
aVthat you get a receptor that doesn't work as well;
p112
aVthe animal lives longer.
p113
aVSo that means that the normal function of this hormone receptor
p114
aVis to speed up aging.
p115
aVThat's what that arrow means.
p116
aVIt speeds up aging. It makes it go faster.
p117
aVSo it's like the animal has the grim reaper inside of itself,
p118
aVspeeding up aging.
p119
aVSo this is altogether really, really interesting.
p120
aVIt says that aging is subject to control by the genes,
p121
aVand specifically by hormones.
p122
aVSo what kind of hormones are these?
p123
aVThere's lots of hormones. There's testosterone, adrenalin.
p124
aVYou know about a lot of them.
p125
aVThese hormones are similar
p126
aVto hormones that we have in our bodies.
p127
aVThe daf-2 hormone receptor
p128
aVis very similar to the receptor
p129
aVfor the hormone insulin and IGF-1.
p130
aa(lp131
VNow you've all heard of at least insulin.
p132
aVInsulin is a hormone that promotes the uptake of nutrients
p133
aVinto your tissues after you eat a meal.
p134
aVAnd the hormone IGF-1 promotes growth.
p135
aVSo these functions were known for these hormones for a long time,
p136
aVbut our studies suggested
p137
aVthat maybe they had a third function that nobody knew about \u2014
p138
aVmaybe they also affect aging.
p139
aVAnd it's looking like that's the case.
p140
aa(lp141
VSo after we made our discoveries with little C. elegans,
p142
aVpeople who worked on other kinds of animals
p143
aVstarted asking, if we made the same daf-2 mutation,
p144
aVthe hormone receptor mutation, in other animals,
p145
aVwill they live longer?
p146
aVAnd that is the case in flies.
p147
aVIf you change this hormone pathway in flies, they live longer.
p148
aVAnd also in mice \u2014 and mice are mammals like us.
p149
aVSo it's an ancient pathway,
p150
aVbecause it must have arisen a long time ago in evolution
p151
aVsuch that it still works in all these animals.
p152
aVAnd also, the common precursor also gave rise to people.
p153
aa(lp154
VSo maybe it's working in people the same way.
p155
aVAnd there are hints of this.
p156
aVSo for example, there was one study that was done
p157
aVin a population of Ashkenazi Jews in New York City.
p158
aVAnd just like any population,
p159
aVmost of the people live to be about 70 or 80,
p160
aVbut some live to be 90 or 100.
p161
aVAnd what they found
p162
aVwas that people who lived to 90 or 100
p163
aVwere more likely to have daf-2 mutations \u2014
p164
aVthat is, changes in the gene
p165
aVthat encodes the receptor for IGF-1.
p166
aVAnd these changes made the gene not act as well
p167
aVas the normal gene would have acted.
p168
aVIt damaged the gene.
p169
aVSo those are hints
p170
aVsuggesting that humans are susceptible
p171
aVto the effects of the hormones for aging.
p172
aa(lp173
VSo the next question, of course, is:
p174
aVIs there any effect on age-related disease?
p175
aVAs you age, you're much more likely
p176
aVto get cancer, Alzheimer's disease,
p177
aVheart disease, all sorts of diseases.
p178
aVIt turns out that these long-lived mutants
p179
aVare more resistant to all these diseases.
p180
aVThey hardly get cancer,
p181
aVand when they do it's not as severe.
p182
aVSo it's really interesting, and it makes sense in a way,
p183
aVthat they're still young,
p184
aVso why would they be getting diseases of aging until their old?
p185
aVSo it suggests
p186
aVthat, if we could have a therapeutic or a pill to take
p187
aVto replicate some of these effects in humans,
p188
aVmaybe we would have a way
p189
aVof combating lots of different age-related diseases
p190
aVall at once.
p191
aVSo how can a hormone ultimately affect the rate of aging?
p192
aVHow could that work?
p193
aa(lp194
VWell it turns out that in the daf-2 mutants,
p195
aVa whole lot of genes are switched on in the DNA
p196
aVthat encode proteins that protect the cells and the tissues,
p197
aVand repair damage.
p198
aVAnd the way that they're switched on
p199
aVis by a gene regulator protein called FOXO.
p200
aVSo in a daf-2 mutant \u2014
p201
aVyou see that I have the X drawn here through the receptor.
p202
aVThe receptor isn't working as well.
p203
aVUnder those conditions, the FOXO protein in blue
p204
aVhas gone into the nucleus \u2014
p205
aVthat little compartment there in the middle of the cell \u2014
p206
aVand it's sitting down on a gene binding to it.
p207
aVYou see one gene. There are lots of genes actually that bind on FOXO.
p208
aVAnd it's just sitting on one of them.
p209
aa(lp210
VSo FOXO turns on a lot of genes.
p211
aVAnd the genes it turns on includes antioxidant genes,
p212
aVgenes I call carrot-giver genes,
p213
aVwhose protein products
p214
aVactually help other proteins to function well \u2014
p215
aVto fold correctly and function correctly.
p216
aVAnd it can also escort them to the garbage cans of the cell
p217
aVand recycle them if they're damaged.
p218
aVDNA repair genes
p219
aVare more active in these animals.
p220
aVAnd the immune system is more active.
p221
aVAnd many of these different genes, we've shown,
p222
aVactually contribute to the long lifespan of the daf-2 mutant.
p223
aVSo it's really interesting.
p224
aVThese animals have within them
p225
aVthe latent capacity to live much longer than they normally do.
p226
aVThey have the ability
p227
aVto protect themselves from many kinds of damage,
p228
aVwhich we think makes them live longer.
p229
aa(lp230
VSo what about the normal worm?
p231
aVWell when the daf-2 receptor is active,
p232
aVthen it triggers a series of events
p233
aVthat prevent FOXO
p234
aVfrom getting into the nucleus where the DNA is.
p235
aVSo it can't turn the genes on.
p236
aVThat's how it works. That's why we don't see the long lifespan,
p237
aVuntil we have the daf-2 mutant.
p238
aVBut what good is this for the worm?
p239
aVWell we think that insulin and IGF-1 hormones
p240
aVare hormones that are particularly active
p241
aVunder favorable conditions \u2014 in the good times \u2014
p242
aVwhen food is plentiful and there's not a lot of stress in the environment.
p243
aVThen they promote the uptake of nutrients.
p244
aVYou can store the food, use it for energy,
p245
aVgrow, etc.
p246
aa(lp247
VBut what we think is that, under conditions of stress,
p248
aVthe levels of these hormones drop \u2014
p249
aVfor example, having limited food supply.
p250
aVAnd that, we think,
p251
aVis registered by the animal as a danger signal,
p252
aVa signal that things are not okay
p253
aVand that it should roll out its protective capacity.
p254
aVSo it activates FOXO, FOXO goes to the DNA,
p255
aVand that triggers the expression of these genes
p256
aVthat improves the ability of the cell
p257
aVto protect itself and repair itself.
p258
aVAnd that's why we think the animals live longer.
p259
aa(lp260
VSo you can think of FOXO
p261
aVas being like a building superintendent.
p262
aVSo maybe he's a little bit lazy,
p263
aVbut he's there, he's taking care of the building.
p264
aVBut it's deteriorating.
p265
aVAnd then suddenly, he learns that there's going to be a hurricane.
p266
aVSo he doesn't actually do anything himself.
p267
aVHe gets on the telephone \u2014
p268
aVjust like FOXO gets on the DNA \u2014
p269
aVand he calls up
p270
aVthe roofer, the window person,
p271
aVthe painter, the floor person.
p272
aVAnd they all come and they fortify the house.
p273
aVAnd then the hurricane comes through,
p274
aVand the house is in much better condition than it would normally have been in.
p275
aVAnd not only that, it can also just last longer,
p276
aVeven if there isn't a hurricane.
p277
aVSo that's the concept here
p278
aVfor how we think this life extension ability exists.
